            "summary": "The U.S. dollar has reached its weakest point in over two years due to weakening inflation and labor market indicators. The U.S. dollar index, which measures its strength against other currencies, dropped to 97.60, the lowest since late March 2022. This decline followed reports showing cooling inflation and a surge in jobless claims. The Producer Price Index rose 2.6% in May, matching expectations but lower than April. Core PPI, excluding food and energy prices, also dropped to 3.0% year-over-year. The Consumer Price Index rose by 2.4% annually in May. Economists are calling for the Federal Reserve to cut interest rates in response to these trends.",
